Sure! You can put the entire switch statement inside a `do..while` loop instead of using a `default` case. Here is an updated code that will keep prompting the user to choose an option until a valid option is selected:

```
do {
    # Prompt the user to select an option
    $choice = Read-Host "Choose an option:`n1. Option One`n2. Option Two`n3. Option Three"

    # Execute code based on user's choice
    switch ($choice) {
        '1' {
            # Code to execute for option one
            Write-Host "You chose Option One"
            $validOption = $true
        }
        '2' {
            # Code to execute for option two
            Write-Host "You chose Option Two"
            $validOption = $true
        }
        '3' {
            # Code to execute for option three
            Write-Host "You chose Option Three"
            $validOption = $true
        }
        default {
            # Code to execute if user inputs an invalid option
            Write-Host "Invalid choice. Please select Option 1, 2, or 3."
            $validOption = $false
        }
    }
}
while (!$validOption)
```

In this version of the code, the `do` loop will continue to execute as long as `$validOption` is `$false`. Within the loop, the user is prompted to choose an option and the `switch` statement executes different sections of your script depending on the user's choice. If an invalid option is selected, the user will be prompted again until a valid option is chosen. When a valid option is selected, `$validOption` is set to `$true` and the loop exits.

